<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="387" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">368.1121 Stephano,
                                Christopher/12</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 185</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-03">May 3, 1935</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your
                                despatch No. 594, of April 5, 1935,<note n="8" xml:id="d387fn8">Not
                                    printed. See footnote 7, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi></note>
                                reporting the release of Mr. Christopher Stephano, who had been
                                under arrest on the charge of high treason in connection with the
                                recent rebellion in Greece. The effective manner in which you and
                                your staff dealt with this case meets with the Department’s
                                commendation.</p>
                            <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                            <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>